## Best Practices and Common Pitfalls

Building robust handlers requires understanding common patterns and avoiding frequent mistakes. Here are battle-tested practices from the OpenMaui.Controls.Linux codebase.

## Best Practices

### 1. Always Unsubscribe Events

The most common memory leak source is forgetting to unsubscribe events:

```csharp
// ❌ BAD: Memory leak
protected override void ConnectHandler(SkiaButton platformView)
{
    platformView.Clicked += OnClicked;
}

// ✅ GOOD: Proper cleanup
protected override void ConnectHandler(SkiaButton platformView)
{
    base.ConnectHandler(platformView);
    platformView.Clicked += OnClicked;
}

protected override void DisconnectHandler(SkiaButton platformView)
{
    platformView.Clicked -= OnClicked;
    base.DisconnectHandler(platformView);
}
```

### 2. Null-Check Platform Views

Property mappers can be called before the platform view is created:

```csharp
// ❌ BAD: Potential NullReferenceException
private static void MapText(ButtonHandler handler, IButton button)
{
    handler.PlatformView.Text = button.Text;
}

// ✅ GOOD: Defensive null check
private static void MapText(ButtonHandler handler, IButton button)
{
    handler.PlatformView?.UpdateText(button.Text);
}
```

### 3. Use Extension Methods for Platform Updates

Extension methods keep mappers clean and testable:

```csharp
// ✅ GOOD: Clean mapper with extension method
private static void MapText(ButtonHandler handler, IButton button)
{
    handler.PlatformView?.UpdateText(button.Text);
}

public static void UpdateText(this SkiaButton button, string? text)
{
    if (button.Text == text) return; // Avoid unnecessary updates

    button.Text = text ?? string.Empty;
    button.Invalidate();
}
```

### 4. Batch Property Updates

When multiple properties change, batch invalidation calls:

```csharp
public static void UpdateFont(this SkiaLabel label, Font font)
{
    label.BeginUpdate();

    try
    {
        label.FontFamily = font.Family;
        label.FontSize = (float)font.Size;
        label.FontWeight = MapFontWeight(font.Weight);
    }
    finally
    {
        label.EndUpdate(); // Single invalidation
    }
}
```

### 5. Implement Proper Disposal

Always dispose SkiaSharp resources:

```csharp
public class SkiaImage : SkiaView, IDisposable
{
    private SKBitmap? _bitmap;
    private bool _disposed;

    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing)
    {
        if (_disposed) return;

        if (disposing)
        {
            _bitmap?.Dispose();
            _bitmap = null;
        }

        _disposed = true;
        base.Dispose(disposing);
    }
}
```

### 6. Use Weak Event Handlers for Long-Lived Subscriptions

For event sources that outlive the handler, use weak references:

```csharp
public class ThemeHandler
{
    private readonly WeakEventManager _weakEventManager = new();

    public void ConnectHandler()
    {
        // Theme service outlives individual handlers
        _weakEventManager.AddEventHandler<ThemeChangedEventArgs>(
            ThemeService.Instance,
            nameof(ThemeService.ThemeChanged),
            OnThemeChanged
        );
    }

    public void DisconnectHandler()
    {
        _weakEventManager.RemoveEventHandler<ThemeChangedEventArgs>(
            ThemeService.Instance,
            nameof(ThemeService.ThemeChanged),
            OnThemeChanged
        );
    }
}
```

### 7. Validate Property Values

Use coercion callbacks to validate property values:

```csharp
public static readonly BindableProperty ValueProperty = 
    BindableProperty.Create(
        nameof(Value),
        typeof(double),
        typeof(Gauge),
        0.0,
        coerceValue: CoerceValue);

private static object CoerceValue(BindableObject bindable, object value)
{
    var gauge = (Gauge)bindable;
    var doubleValue = (double)value;

    // Clamp value between min and max
    return Math.Max(gauge.Minimum, Math.Min(gauge.Maximum, doubleValue));
}
```

## Common Pitfalls

### Pitfall 1: Forgetting Base Class Calls

```csharp
// ❌ BAD: Skips base initialization
protected override void ConnectHandler(SkiaButton platformView)
{
    platformView.Clicked += OnClicked;
}

// ✅ GOOD: Calls base first
protected override void ConnectHandler(SkiaButton platformView)
{
    base.ConnectHandler(platformView); // CRITICAL
    platformView.Clicked += OnClicked;
}
```

### Pitfall 2: Circular Property Updates

Two-way binding can cause infinite loops:

```csharp
// ❌ BAD: Causes infinite loop
private void OnTextChanged(object? sender, TextChangedEventArgs e)
{
    VirtualView.Text = e.NewTextValue; // Triggers mapper
}

private static void MapText(EntryHandler handler, IEntry entry)
{
    handler.PlatformView.Text = entry.Text; // Triggers TextChanged
}

// ✅ GOOD: Check for actual changes
private void OnTextChanged(object? sender, TextChangedEventArgs e)
{
    if (VirtualView.Text != e.NewTextValue)
    {
        VirtualView.Text = e.NewTextValue;
    }
}

private static void MapText(EntryHandler handler, IEntry entry)
{
    if (handler.PlatformView.Text != entry.Text)
    {
        handler.PlatformView.Text = entry.Text;
    }
}
```

### Pitfall 3: Ignoring Thread Safety

```csharp
// ❌ BAD: Updates UI from background thread
private async Task LoadImageAsync(string url)
{
    var bitmap = await DownloadImageAsync(url);
    PlatformView.Bitmap = bitmap; // May be called on background thread
}

// ✅ GOOD: Dispatches to UI thread
private async Task LoadImageAsync(string url)
{
    var bitmap = await DownloadImageAsync(url);

    await Dispatcher.DispatchAsync(() =>
    {
        PlatformView.Bitmap = bitmap;
    });
}
```

### Pitfall 4: Premature Optimization

```csharp
// ❌ BAD: Complex caching before profiling
private static readonly ConcurrentDictionary<string, SKTypeface> _typefaceCache = new();

private static void MapFont(LabelHandler handler, ILabel label)
{
    var key = $"{label.FontFamily}_{label.FontSize}_{label.FontAttributes}";
    var typeface = _typefaceCache.GetOrAdd(key, _ => CreateTypeface(label));
    handler.PlatformView.Typeface = typeface;
}

// ✅ GOOD: Simple implementation first, optimize if needed
private static void MapFont(LabelHandler handler, ILabel label)
{
    var typeface = CreateTypeface(label);
    handler.PlatformView.Typeface = typeface;
}
```

Profile before optimizing. OpenMaui's `TextRenderCache` was added only after profiling showed text shaping was a bottleneck.

### Pitfall 5: Tight Coupling to Platform Implementation

```csharp
// ❌ BAD: Handler knows too much about platform internals
private static void MapText(ButtonHandler handler, IButton button)
{
    var skiaButton = handler.PlatformView;
    skiaButton._textPaint.Color = button.TextColor.ToSKColor();
    skiaButton._textPaint.TextSize = (float)button.FontSize;
    skiaButton.QueueDraw();
}

// ✅ GOOD: Uses platform view's public API
private static void MapText(ButtonHandler handler, IButton button)
{
    handler.PlatformView?.UpdateText(button.Text);
}
```

Keep handlers focused on mapping, not implementation details.

## Testing Handlers

OpenMaui includes comprehensive handler tests:

```csharp
public class ButtonHandlerTests
{
    [Fact]
    public void MapText_UpdatesPlatformView()
    {
        // Arrange
        var button = new Button { Text = "Click Me" };
        var handler = new ButtonHandler();
        handler.SetVirtualView(button);
        var platformView = handler.CreatePlatformView();
        handler.SetPlatformView(platformView);

        // Act
        ButtonHandler.MapText(handler, button);

        // Assert
        platformView.Text.Should().Be("Click Me");
    }

    [Fact]
    public void Clicked_RaisesVirtualViewEvent()
    {
        // Arrange
        var button = new Button();
        var handler = new ButtonHandler();
        handler.SetVirtualView(button);
        var platformView = handler.CreatePlatformView();
        handler.SetPlatformView(platformView);
        handler.ConnectHandler(platformView);

        var eventRaised = false;
        button.Clicked += (s, e) => eventRaised = true;

        // Act
        platformView.SimulateClick();

        // Assert
        eventRaised.Should().BeTrue();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void DisconnectHandler_UnsubscribesEvents()
    {
        // Arrange
        var button = new Button();
        var handler = new ButtonHandler();
        handler.SetVirtualView(button);
        var platformView = handler.CreatePlatformView();
        handler.ConnectHandler(platformView);

        // Act
        handler.DisconnectHandler(platformView);

        var eventRaised = false;
        button.Clicked += (s, e) => eventRaised = true;
        platformView.SimulateClick();

        // Assert
        eventRaised.Should().BeFalse();
    }
}
```

## Performance Tips

1. **Profile Before Optimizing**: Use OpenMaui's built-in performance benchmarks to identify bottlenecks
2. **Cache Expensive Resources**: Typefaces, bitmaps, and shaped text benefit from caching
3. **Use Dirty Region Tracking**: Only redraw changed areas, not the entire view
4. **Batch Updates**: Group property changes to minimize invalidation calls
5. **Virtualize Collections**: Use `CollectionView` with recycling for large datasets
6. **Enable GPU Acceleration**: OpenMaui defaults to hardware rendering—ensure it's enabled
7. **Minimize Allocations**: Reuse SKPaint objects and avoid creating new objects in draw loops

By following these practices and avoiding common pitfalls, you'll create handlers that are performant, maintainable, and leak-free—essential qualities for production MAUI applications on Linux.

---

> Handlers are the invisible bridge between MAUI's cross-platform abstraction and the platform-specific rendering reality—they map virtual controls to concrete Skia views while maintaining 100% API compatibility.

> Property mappers don't just copy values; they translate MAUI's platform-agnostic types into rendering instructions that SkiaSharp can execute on Linux.

> Creating a custom handler means thinking in two worlds simultaneously: the MAUI control's public API and the platform view's rendering implementation.

sections.content:
Let's dissect the `ButtonHandler` to understand how handlers work under the hood. The button is one of the most fundamental controls, yet its handler demonstrates all the core concepts you'll encounter.

## Handler Structure

Every handler in OpenMaui follows this basic structure:

```csharp
public class ButtonHandler : ViewHandler<IButton, SkiaButton>
{
    // Property mapper defines how MAUI properties sync to platform view
    public static IPropertyMapper<IButton, ButtonHandler> Mapper = 
        new PropertyMapper<IButton, ButtonHandler>(ViewHandler.ViewMapper)
        {
            [nameof(IButton.Text)] = MapText,
            [nameof(IButton.TextColor)] = MapTextColor,
            [nameof(IButton.Background)] = MapBackground,
            [nameof(IButton.BorderColor)] = MapBorderColor,
            [nameof(IButton.BorderWidth)] = MapBorderWidth,
            [nameof(IButton.CornerRadius)] = MapCornerRadius,
            [nameof(IButton.Padding)] = MapPadding,
            [nameof(IButton.CharacterSpacing)] = MapCharacterSpacing,
            [nameof(IButton.Font)] = MapFont,
            [nameof(IButton.ImageSource)] = MapImageSource
        };

    // Command mapper handles user interactions
    public static CommandMapper<IButton, ButtonHandler> CommandMapper = 
        new(ViewCommandMapper)
        {
            [nameof(IButton.Clicked)] = MapClicked
        };

    public ButtonHandler() : base(Mapper, CommandMapper)
    {
    }

    // Creates the platform-specific view
    protected override SkiaButton CreatePlatformView()
    {
        return new SkiaButton();
    }

    // Connects platform events to MAUI control
    protected override void ConnectHandler(SkiaButton platformView)
    {
        base.ConnectHandler(platformView);
        platformView.Clicked += OnPlatformClicked;
    }

    // Disconnects events to prevent memory leaks
    protected override void DisconnectHandler(SkiaButton platformView)
    {
        platformView.Clicked -= OnPlatformClicked;
        base.DisconnectHandler(platformView);
    }

    private void OnPlatformClicked(object? sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        VirtualView?.Clicked();
    }
}
```

## Key Components Explained

**Generic Type Parameters**: `ViewHandler<IButton, SkiaButton>` specifies two types:
- `IButton` - The MAUI virtual view interface
- `SkiaButton` - The platform-specific Skia view

This generic approach provides type safety while allowing handlers to work with MAUI's abstraction layer.

**VirtualView vs PlatformView**: Every handler maintains references to both:
- `VirtualView` (IButton) - The cross-platform MAUI control
- `PlatformView` (SkiaButton) - The platform-specific rendering implementation

Property mappers synchronize state from VirtualView to PlatformView, while event handlers route platform events back to the VirtualView.

**CreatePlatformView**: This method instantiates the Skia-rendered view. For ButtonHandler, it creates a `SkiaButton` instance that will handle all rendering using SkiaSharp's canvas API.

**ConnectHandler/DisconnectHandler**: These lifecycle methods manage event subscriptions. `ConnectHandler` wires up platform events (like button clicks) to MAUI control methods. `DisconnectHandler` cleans up to prevent memory leaks—a critical step often overlooked in custom handlers.

## The Platform View: SkiaButton

The `SkiaButton` class is where rendering actually happens:

```csharp
public class SkiaButton : SkiaView
{
    protected override void OnDraw(SKCanvas canvas)
    {
        base.OnDraw(canvas);

        // Draw background with corner radius
        using var bgPaint = new SKPaint
        {
            IsAntialias = true,
            Color = BackgroundColor.ToSKColor(),
            Style = SKPaintStyle.Fill
        };

        var rect = new SKRect(0, 0, Width, Height);
        canvas.DrawRoundRect(rect, CornerRadius, CornerRadius, bgPaint);

        // Draw border if specified
        if (BorderWidth > 0)
        {
            using var borderPaint = new SKPaint
            {
                IsAntialias = true,
                Color = BorderColor.ToSKColor(),
                Style = SKPaintStyle.Stroke,
                StrokeWidth = (float)BorderWidth
            };
            canvas.DrawRoundRect(rect, CornerRadius, CornerRadius, borderPaint);
        }

        // Draw text centered
        if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(Text))
        {
            using var textPaint = new SKPaint
            {
                IsAntialias = true,
                Color = TextColor.ToSKColor(),
                TextSize = (float)FontSize,
                Typeface = GetTypeface(),
                TextAlign = SKTextAlign.Center
            };

            var textBounds = new SKRect();
            textPaint.MeasureText(Text, ref textBounds);

            var x = Width / 2;
            var y = (Height - textBounds.Height) / 2 - textBounds.Top;

            canvas.DrawText(Text, x, y, textPaint);
        }
    }
}
```

This rendering approach gives OpenMaui complete control over visual appearance, enabling consistent behavior across GNOME, KDE, XFCE, and other Linux desktop environments.

Property mappers are the heart of the handler architecture. They define how changes to MAUI control properties propagate to the platform view. Understanding mappers is essential for creating responsive, performant applications.

## How Property Mapping Works

When you set a property on a MAUI control:

```csharp
var button = new Button 
{ 
    Text = "Click Me",
    TextColor = Colors.White,
    BackgroundColor = Colors.Blue
};
```

The handler's property mapper intercepts each property change and invokes the corresponding mapping function. Here's how the `Text` property maps:

```csharp
public static void MapText(ButtonHandler handler, IButton button)
{
    handler.PlatformView?.UpdateText(button.Text);
}
```

The mapper receives both the handler (providing access to the platform view) and the virtual view (providing the new property value). It then calls platform-specific update methods.

## Type Translation

One of the mapper's critical responsibilities is **type translation**. MAUI uses platform-agnostic types like `Microsoft.Maui.Graphics.Color`, `Thickness`, and `CornerRadius`. The platform view needs SkiaSharp types like `SKColor` and `float` values.

Here's the color mapping pattern used throughout OpenMaui:

```csharp
public static void MapTextColor(ButtonHandler handler, IButton button)
{
    var platformView = handler.PlatformView;
    if (platformView == null) return;

    // Convert MAUI Color to SKColor
    var skColor = button.TextColor.ToSKColor();
    platformView.TextColor = skColor;

    // Trigger redraw
    platformView.Invalidate();
}

// Extension method for color conversion
public static SKColor ToSKColor(this Color color)
{
    return new SKColor(
        (byte)(color.Red * 255),
        (byte)(color.Green * 255),
        (byte)(color.Blue * 255),
        (byte)(color.Alpha * 255)
    );
}
```

## Complex Property Mapping: Fonts

Some properties require more sophisticated mapping. The `Font` property in MAUI encapsulates family, size, weight, and style—all of which must be translated to SkiaSharp's `SKTypeface` and `SKPaint` settings:

```csharp
public static void MapFont(LabelHandler handler, ILabel label)
{
    var platformView = handler.PlatformView;
    if (platformView == null) return;

    // Extract font properties
    var family = label.Font.Family ?? "sans-serif";
    var size = label.Font.Size > 0 ? label.Font.Size : 14.0;
    var weight = label.Font.Weight;
    var slant = label.FontAttributes.HasFlag(FontAttributes.Italic) 
        ? SKFontStyleSlant.Italic 
        : SKFontStyleSlant.Upright;

    // Map MAUI FontWeight to Skia weight value
    var skWeight = weight switch
    {
        >= 700 => SKFontStyleWeight.Bold,
        >= 600 => SKFontStyleWeight.SemiBold,
        >= 500 => SKFontStyleWeight.Medium,
        _ => SKFontStyleWeight.Normal
    };

    // Create typeface with font fallback support
    var typeface = SKTypeface.FromFamilyName(
        family,
        skWeight,
        SKFontStyleWidth.Normal,
        slant
    ) ?? SKTypeface.Default;

    platformView.Typeface = typeface;
    platformView.FontSize = (float)size;
    platformView.Invalidate();
}
```

This mapping demonstrates OpenMaui's **font fallback system**, which ensures emoji and CJK characters render correctly even when the specified font doesn't support them.

## Chaining and Inheritance

Property mappers support inheritance through chaining. The `ButtonHandler` mapper chains from `ViewHandler.ViewMapper`, which provides base mappings for properties like `Background`, `Width`, `Height`, and `IsEnabled`:

```csharp
public static IPropertyMapper<IButton, ButtonHandler> Mapper = 
    new PropertyMapper<IButton, ButtonHandler>(ViewHandler.ViewMapper)
    {
        // Button-specific mappings
        [nameof(IButton.Text)] = MapText,
        [nameof(IButton.TextColor)] = MapTextColor,
        // ... more mappings
    };
```

This pattern enables code reuse while allowing derived handlers to override base mappings when needed.

## Performance Considerations

Property mappers are called frequently, so performance matters:

**Batch Updates**: OpenMaui's `SkiaRenderingEngine` uses dirty region tracking to minimize redraws. When multiple properties change, the platform batches invalidation calls:

```csharp
public void BeginUpdate()
{
    _isUpdating = true;
}

public void EndUpdate()
{
    _isUpdating = false;
    if (_needsInvalidation)
    {
        Invalidate();
        _needsInvalidation = false;
    }
}

public void Invalidate()
{
    if (_isUpdating)
    {
        _needsInvalidation = true;
    }
    else
    {
        // Trigger actual redraw
        QueueDraw();
    }
}
```

**Caching**: Text rendering uses `TextRenderCache` to avoid re-shaping text on every frame:

```csharp
private static readonly TextRenderCache _textCache = new();

public static void MapText(LabelHandler handler, ILabel label)
{
    var platformView = handler.PlatformView;
    if (platformView == null) return;

    // Cache key includes text and font properties
    var cacheKey = $"{label.Text}_{label.Font.Family}_{label.Font.Size}";

    if (!_textCache.TryGet(cacheKey, out var shapedText))
    {
        // Expensive text shaping with HarfBuzz
        shapedText = ShapeText(label.Text, label.Font);
        _textCache.Add(cacheKey, shapedText);
    }

    platformView.ShapedText = shapedText;
    platformView.Invalidate();
}
```

This caching strategy is crucial for performance in scrolling scenarios like `CollectionView`, where the same text might render hundreds of times.

While property mappers handle state synchronization, **command mappers** manage user interactions and events. They route platform-specific events (mouse clicks, key presses, touch gestures) back to the MAUI control's event handlers and command bindings.

## Command Mapper Basics

Command mappers follow a similar pattern to property mappers but handle discrete actions rather than continuous state:

```csharp
public static CommandMapper<IButton, ButtonHandler> CommandMapper = 
    new(ViewCommandMapper)
    {
        [nameof(IButton.Clicked)] = MapClicked
    };

private static void MapClicked(ButtonHandler handler, IButton button, object? args)
{
    // Platform view has already raised its Clicked event
    // This mapper can perform additional platform-specific logic
    handler.PlatformView?.PerformHapticFeedback();
}
```

Unlike property mappers, command mappers typically don't need to do much work—the heavy lifting happens in the handler's `ConnectHandler` method where platform events are wired up.

## Event Routing Pattern

Here's the complete event routing flow for a button click:

```csharp
public class ButtonHandler : ViewHandler<IButton, SkiaButton>
{
    protected override void ConnectHandler(SkiaButton platformView)
    {
        base.ConnectHandler(platformView);

        // Subscribe to platform view's event
        platformView.Clicked += OnPlatformClicked;
    }

    protected override void DisconnectHandler(SkiaButton platformView)
    {
        // CRITICAL: Unsubscribe to prevent memory leaks
        platformView.Clicked -= OnPlatformClicked;
        base.DisconnectHandler(platformView);
    }

    private void OnPlatformClicked(object? sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // Route to MAUI control's event
        VirtualView?.Clicked();

        // Also invoke Command if bound
        if (VirtualView?.Command?.CanExecute(VirtualView.CommandParameter) == true)
        {
            VirtualView.Command.Execute(VirtualView.CommandParameter);
        }
    }
}
```

## Input Event Translation

More complex controls require translating platform-specific input events to MAUI's gesture recognizer system. The `EntryHandler` demonstrates this for text input:

```csharp
public class EntryHandler : ViewHandler<IEntry, SkiaEntry>
{
    protected override void ConnectHandler(SkiaEntry platformView)
    {
        base.ConnectHandler(platformView);

        platformView.TextChanged += OnTextChanged;
        platformView.Focused += OnFocused;
        platformView.Unfocused += OnUnfocused;
        platformView.Completed += OnCompleted;
    }

    private void OnTextChanged(object? sender, TextChangedEventArgs e)
    {
        // Update MAUI control's Text property
        if (VirtualView != null)
        {
            VirtualView.Text = e.NewTextValue;
        }
    }

    private void OnFocused(object? sender, FocusEventArgs e)
    {
        if (VirtualView != null)
        {
            // Trigger MAUI's focus handling
            VirtualView.IsFocused = true;
            VirtualView.Focused?.Invoke(this, e);
        }
    }

    private void OnCompleted(object? sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // User pressed Enter/Return
        VirtualView?.Completed?.Invoke(this, e);

        // Execute ReturnCommand if bound
        if (VirtualView?.ReturnCommand?.CanExecute(VirtualView.ReturnCommandParameter) == true)
        {
            VirtualView.ReturnCommand.Execute(VirtualView.ReturnCommandParameter);
        }
    }
}
```

## Gesture Recognition

OpenMaui implements MAUI's gesture recognizer system through the `SkiaView` base class, which all platform views inherit:

```csharp
public abstract class SkiaView
{
    private readonly List<IGestureRecognizer> _gestureRecognizers = new();

    public void AddGestureRecognizer(IGestureRecognizer recognizer)
    {
        _gestureRecognizers.Add(recognizer);
    }

    protected virtual void OnPointerPressed(PointerEventArgs e)
    {
        foreach (var recognizer in _gestureRecognizers)
        {
            if (recognizer is TapGestureRecognizer tap)
            {
                tap.OnTapped(this, e);
            }
            else if (recognizer is PanGestureRecognizer pan)
            {
                pan.OnPanStarted(this, e);
            }
            // ... other gesture types
        }
    }

    protected virtual void OnPointerMoved(PointerEventArgs e)
    {
        foreach (var recognizer in _gestureRecognizers)
        {
            if (recognizer is PanGestureRecognizer pan && pan.IsTracking)
            {
                pan.OnPanUpdated(this, e);
            }
            else if (recognizer is SwipeGestureRecognizer swipe)
            {
                swipe.OnPointerMoved(this, e);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Handlers connect these gesture recognizers during initialization:

```csharp
protected override void ConnectHandler(SkiaView platformView)
{
    base.ConnectHandler(platformView);

    // Add MAUI control's gesture recognizers to platform view
    if (VirtualView is IView view)
    {
        foreach (var recognizer in view.GestureRecognizers)
        {
            platformView.AddGestureRecognizer(recognizer);
        }
    }
}
```

## Threading and Dispatching

Linux platform events can arrive on different threads, but MAUI controls must be updated on the UI thread. OpenMaui uses `LinuxDispatcher` for thread-safe event routing:

```csharp
private void OnPlatformClicked(object? sender, EventArgs e)
{
    // Ensure we're on the UI thread
    if (!Dispatcher.IsDispatchRequired)
    {
        VirtualView?.Clicked();
    }
    else
    {
        Dispatcher.Dispatch(() => VirtualView?.Clicked());
    }
}
```

The dispatcher uses GTK's GLib main loop for thread-safe marshaling, ensuring all MAUI control updates happen on the correct thread.

Proper lifecycle management is critical for preventing memory leaks and ensuring clean resource cleanup. Handlers orchestrate the creation, connection, and disposal of platform views throughout their lifetime.

## Handler Lifecycle Phases

Every handler goes through these phases:

1. **Creation**: `CreatePlatformView()` instantiates the platform-specific view
2. **Connection**: `ConnectHandler()` wires up events and initializes state
3. **Property Sync**: Mappers synchronize initial property values
4. **Active Use**: Events flow between platform view and virtual view
5. **Disconnection**: `DisconnectHandler()` removes event handlers
6. **Disposal**: Platform view and handler resources are released

## The CreatePlatformView Pattern

This method is called once when the handler is first initialized:

```csharp
protected override SkiaButton CreatePlatformView()
{
    var button = new SkiaButton
    {
        // Set default platform-specific properties
        AccessibilityRole = AccessibilityRole.Button,
        Focusable = true
    };

    return button;
}
```

Keep this method lightweight—it should only create the view, not configure it. Property mappers handle configuration after creation.

## ConnectHandler: Wiring Events

`ConnectHandler` is where event subscriptions happen:

```csharp
protected override void ConnectHandler(SkiaButton platformView)
{
    base.ConnectHandler(platformView);

    // Subscribe to platform events
    platformView.Clicked += OnPlatformClicked;
    platformView.Pressed += OnPlatformPressed;
    platformView.Released += OnPlatformReleased;

    // Initialize accessibility
    UpdateAccessibilityLabel();
    UpdateAccessibilityHint();

    // Apply initial visual state
    VisualStateManager.GoToState(VirtualView, "Normal");
}
```

**Critical**: Always call `base.ConnectHandler()` first to ensure base class initialization completes.

## DisconnectHandler: Preventing Memory Leaks

This is the most commonly forgotten but critical lifecycle method:

```csharp
protected override void DisconnectHandler(SkiaButton platformView)
{
    // Unsubscribe ALL event handlers
    platformView.Clicked -= OnPlatformClicked;
    platformView.Pressed -= OnPlatformPressed;
    platformView.Released -= OnPlatformReleased;

    // Clean up platform resources
    platformView.Dispose();

    // ALWAYS call base last
    base.DisconnectHandler(platformView);
}
```

**Memory Leak Warning**: Failing to unsubscribe events creates strong references that prevent garbage collection. This is especially problematic in navigation scenarios where pages are frequently created and destroyed.

## Platform View Disposal

Skia views implement `IDisposable` to clean up graphics resources:

```csharp
public class SkiaButton : SkiaView, IDisposable
{
    private SKTypeface? _typeface;
    private SKBitmap? _iconBitmap;
    private bool _disposed;

    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing)
    {
        if (_disposed) return;

        if (disposing)
        {
            // Dispose managed resources
            _typeface?.Dispose();
            _iconBitmap?.Dispose();

            // Clear event handlers
            Clicked = null;
            Pressed = null;
            Released = null;
        }

        _disposed = true;
        base.Dispose(disposing);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Dispose(true);
        GC.SuppressFinalize(this);
    }
}
```

SkiaSharp objects like `SKTypeface`, `SKPaint`, and `SKBitmap` are unmanaged resources that must be explicitly disposed.

## Complex Lifecycle: CollectionView

Collection views demonstrate advanced lifecycle management with view recycling:

```csharp
public class CollectionViewHandler : ViewHandler<ICollectionView, SkiaCollectionView>
{
    private readonly Dictionary<object, ViewCell> _recycledCells = new();

    protected override void ConnectHandler(SkiaCollectionView platformView)
    {
        base.ConnectHandler(platformView);

        platformView.ItemsSource = VirtualView?.ItemsSource;
        platformView.CellRequested += OnCellRequested;
        platformView.CellRecycled += OnCellRecycled;
    }

    private ViewCell OnCellRequested(object item)
    {
        // Try to reuse a recycled cell
        if (_recycledCells.TryGetValue(item.GetType(), out var cell))
        {
            _recycledCells.Remove(item.GetType());
            cell.BindingContext = item;
            return cell;
        }

        // Create new cell from template
        var template = VirtualView?.ItemTemplate;
        var newCell = (ViewCell)template.CreateContent();
        newCell.BindingContext = item;

        return newCell;
    }

    private void OnCellRecycled(ViewCell cell)
    {
        // Store for reuse
        var itemType = cell.BindingContext?.GetType();
        if (itemType != null)
        {
            _recycledCells[itemType] = cell;
        }
    }

    protected override void DisconnectHandler(SkiaCollectionView platformView)
    {
        // Dispose all recycled cells
        foreach (var cell in _recycledCells.Values)
        {
            (cell as IDisposable)?.Dispose();
        }
        _recycledCells.Clear();

        platformView.CellRequested -= OnCellRequested;
        platformView.CellRecycled -= OnCellRecycled;

        base.DisconnectHandler(platformView);
    }
}
```

This pattern minimizes allocations during scrolling by reusing cell views.

## Navigation Lifecycle

Navigation handlers manage page stack lifecycle:

```csharp
public class NavigationPageHandler : ViewHandler<INavigationPage, SkiaNavigationPage>
{
    protected override void ConnectHandler(SkiaNavigationPage platformView)
    {
        base.ConnectHandler(platformView);

        platformView.PushRequested += OnPushRequested;
        platformView.PopRequested += OnPopRequested;

        // Push initial page
        if (VirtualView?.CurrentPage != null)
        {
            PushPage(VirtualView.CurrentPage);
        }
    }

    private void OnPopRequested(object? sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        if (VirtualView?.Navigation.NavigationStack.Count > 1)
        {
            var page = VirtualView.Navigation.NavigationStack.Last();

            // Trigger page lifecycle
            page.SendDisappearing();

            // Remove from stack
            VirtualView.Navigation.RemovePage(page);

            // Dispose page handler
            var handler = page.Handler as IViewHandler;
            handler?.DisconnectHandler();
        }
    }

    protected override void DisconnectHandler(SkiaNavigationPage platformView)
    {
        // Disconnect all pages in stack
        foreach (var page in VirtualView?.Navigation.NavigationStack ?? Enumerable.Empty<Page>())
        {
            var handler = page.Handler as IViewHandler;
            handler?.DisconnectHandler();
        }

        platformView.PushRequested -= OnPushRequested;
        platformView.PopRequested -= OnPopRequested;

        base.DisconnectHandler(platformView);
    }
}
```

Proper navigation lifecycle ensures pages are fully cleaned up when popped from the stack.

Creating custom handlers lets you build specialized controls that integrate seamlessly with MAUI's architecture. Whether you're wrapping a third-party library or implementing unique functionality, the handler pattern provides a clean abstraction.

## When to Create a Custom Handler

Consider creating a custom handler when you need to:

- **Wrap platform-specific functionality** not available in MAUI (e.g., a Linux-specific system tray icon)
- **Optimize rendering** for specialized scenarios (e.g., a high-performance chart control)
- **Integrate third-party libraries** (e.g., a video player using GStreamer)
- **Implement custom drawing** beyond what `GraphicsView` provides

## Step-by-Step: Creating a Custom Gauge Control

Let's build a circular gauge control to demonstrate the complete process.

### Step 1: Define the MAUI Interface

```csharp
public interface IGauge : IView
{
    double Value { get; }
    double Minimum { get; }
    double Maximum { get; }
    Color ForegroundColor { get; }
    Color BackgroundColor { get; }
    double StrokeWidth { get; }
}
```

### Step 2: Create the MAUI Control

```csharp
public class Gauge : View, IGauge
{
    public static readonly BindableProperty ValueProperty = 
        BindableProperty.Create(
            nameof(Value),
            typeof(double),
            typeof(Gauge),
            0.0,
            propertyChanged: OnValueChanged);

    public double Value
    {
        get => (double)GetValue(ValueProperty);
        set => SetValue(ValueProperty, value);
    }

    public static readonly BindableProperty MinimumProperty = 
        BindableProperty.Create(nameof(Minimum), typeof(double), typeof(Gauge), 0.0);

    public double Minimum
    {
        get => (double)GetValue(MinimumProperty);
        set => SetValue(MinimumProperty, value);
    }

    public static readonly BindableProperty MaximumProperty = 
        BindableProperty.Create(nameof(Maximum), typeof(double), typeof(Gauge), 100.0);

    public double Maximum
    {
        get => (double)GetValue(MaximumProperty);
        set => SetValue(MaximumProperty, value);
    }

    public static readonly BindableProperty ForegroundColorProperty = 
        BindableProperty.Create(nameof(ForegroundColor), typeof(Color), typeof(Gauge), Colors.Blue);

    public Color ForegroundColor
    {
        get => (Color)GetValue(ForegroundColorProperty);
        set => SetValue(ForegroundColorProperty, value);
    }

    public static readonly BindableProperty BackgroundColorProperty = 
        BindableProperty.Create(nameof(BackgroundColor), typeof(Color), typeof(Gauge), Colors.LightGray);

    public Color BackgroundColor
    {
        get => (Color)GetValue(BackgroundColorProperty);
        set => SetValue(BackgroundColorProperty, value);
    }

    public static readonly BindableProperty StrokeWidthProperty = 
        BindableProperty.Create(nameof(StrokeWidth), typeof(double), typeof(Gauge), 10.0);

    public double StrokeWidth
    {
        get => (double)GetValue(StrokeWidthProperty);
        set => SetValue(StrokeWidthProperty, value);
    }

    private static void OnValueChanged(BindableObject bindable, object oldValue, object newValue)
    {
        // Value changed event can be raised here
        var gauge = (Gauge)bindable;
        gauge.ValueChanged?.Invoke(gauge, EventArgs.Empty);
    }

    public event EventHandler? ValueChanged;
}
```

### Step 3: Create the Platform View

```csharp
public class SkiaGauge : SkiaView
{
    private double _value;
    private double _minimum;
    private double _maximum = 100;
    private SKColor _foregroundColor = SKColors.Blue;
    private SKColor _backgroundColor = SKColors.LightGray;
    private float _strokeWidth = 10f;

    public double Value
    {
        get => _value;
        set
        {
            if (_value != value)
            {
                _value = value;
                Invalidate();
            }
        }
    }

    public double Minimum
    {
        get => _minimum;
        set { _minimum = value; Invalidate(); }
    }

    public double Maximum
    {
        get => _maximum;
        set { _maximum = value; Invalidate(); }
    }

    public SKColor ForegroundColor
    {
        get => _foregroundColor;
        set { _foregroundColor = value; Invalidate(); }
    }

    public SKColor BackgroundColor
    {
        get => _backgroundColor;
        set { _backgroundColor = value; Invalidate(); }
    }

    public float StrokeWidth
    {
        get => _strokeWidth;
        set { _strokeWidth = value; Invalidate(); }
    }

    protected override void OnDraw(SKCanvas canvas)
    {
        base.OnDraw(canvas);

        var centerX = Width / 2;
        var centerY = Height / 2;
        var radius = Math.Min(Width, Height) / 2 - _strokeWidth;

        var rect = new SKRect(
            centerX - radius,
            centerY - radius,
            centerX + radius,
            centerY + radius
        );

        // Draw background arc
        using var bgPaint = new SKPaint
        {
            IsAntialias = true,
            Style = SKPaintStyle.Stroke,
            StrokeWidth = _strokeWidth,
            Color = _backgroundColor,
            StrokeCap = SKStrokeCap.Round
        };

        canvas.DrawArc(rect, 135, 270, false, bgPaint);

        // Draw foreground arc based on value
        var normalizedValue = (_value - _minimum) / (_maximum - _minimum);
        var sweepAngle = (float)(normalizedValue * 270);

        using var fgPaint = new SKPaint
        {
            IsAntialias = true,
            Style = SKPaintStyle.Stroke,
            StrokeWidth = _strokeWidth,
            Color = _foregroundColor,
            StrokeCap = SKStrokeCap.Round
        };

        canvas.DrawArc(rect, 135, sweepAngle, false, fgPaint);

        // Draw value text
        var valueText = _value.ToString("F1");
        using var textPaint = new SKPaint
        {
            IsAntialias = true,
            Color = SKColors.Black,
            TextSize = radius / 2,
            TextAlign = SKTextAlign.Center,
            Typeface = SKTypeface.FromFamilyName("sans-serif", SKFontStyleWeight.Bold, SKFontStyleWidth.Normal, SKFontStyleSlant.Upright)
        };

        var textBounds = new SKRect();
        textPaint.MeasureText(valueText, ref textBounds);

        canvas.DrawText(valueText, centerX, centerY - textBounds.MidY, textPaint);
    }
}
```

### Step 4: Create the Handler

```csharp
public class GaugeHandler : ViewHandler<IGauge, SkiaGauge>
{
    public static IPropertyMapper<IGauge, GaugeHandler> Mapper = 
        new PropertyMapper<IGauge, GaugeHandler>(ViewHandler.ViewMapper)
        {
            [nameof(IGauge.Value)] = MapValue,
            [nameof(IGauge.Minimum)] = MapMinimum,
            [nameof(IGauge.Maximum)] = MapMaximum,
            [nameof(IGauge.ForegroundColor)] = MapForegroundColor,
            [nameof(IGauge.BackgroundColor)] = MapBackgroundColor,
            [nameof(IGauge.StrokeWidth)] = MapStrokeWidth
        };

    public GaugeHandler() : base(Mapper)
    {
    }

    protected override SkiaGauge CreatePlatformView()
    {
        return new SkiaGauge();
    }

    private static void MapValue(GaugeHandler handler, IGauge gauge)
    {
        handler.PlatformView?.UpdateValue(gauge.Value);
    }

    private static void MapMinimum(GaugeHandler handler, IGauge gauge)
    {
        handler.PlatformView?.UpdateMinimum(gauge.Minimum);
    }

    private static void MapMaximum(GaugeHandler handler, IGauge gauge)
    {
        handler.PlatformView?.UpdateMaximum(gauge.Maximum);
    }

    private static void MapForegroundColor(GaugeHandler handler, IGauge gauge)
    {
        handler.PlatformView?.UpdateForegroundColor(gauge.ForegroundColor.ToSKColor());
    }

    private static void MapBackgroundColor(GaugeHandler handler, IGauge gauge)
    {
        handler.PlatformView?.UpdateBackgroundColor(gauge.BackgroundColor.ToSKColor());
    }

    private static void MapStrokeWidth(GaugeHandler handler, IGauge gauge)
    {
        handler.PlatformView?.UpdateStrokeWidth((float)gauge.StrokeWidth);
    }
}

// Extension methods for cleaner mapping
public static class SkiaGaugeExtensions
{
    public static void UpdateValue(this SkiaGauge gauge, double value)
    {
        gauge.Value = value;
    }

    public static void UpdateMinimum(this SkiaGauge gauge, double minimum)
    {
        gauge.Minimum = minimum;
    }

    public static void UpdateMaximum(this SkiaGauge gauge, double maximum)
    {
        gauge.Maximum = maximum;
    }

    public static void UpdateForegroundColor(this SkiaGauge gauge, SKColor color)
    {
        gauge.ForegroundColor = color;
    }

    public static void UpdateBackgroundColor(this SkiaGauge gauge, SKColor color)
    {
        gauge.BackgroundColor = color;
    }

    public static void UpdateStrokeWidth(this SkiaGauge gauge, float width)
    {
        gauge.StrokeWidth = width;
    }
}
```

### Step 5: Register the Handler

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder
            .UseMauiApp<App>()
            .ConfigureMauiHandlers(handlers =>
            {
                // Register custom handler
                handlers.AddHandler<Gauge, GaugeHandler>();
            });

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

### Step 6: Use the Control

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             xmlns:local="clr-namespace:MyApp.Controls"
             x:Class="MyApp.MainPage">
    <StackLayout Padding="20">
        <local:Gauge Value="{Binding Temperature}"
                     Minimum="0"
                     Maximum="100"
                     ForegroundColor="Orange"
                     BackgroundColor="LightGray"
